Your sql statement is missing the where clause thus its causing all your `pets` to be updated to all be of the same value and one of those values looks to be the primary key which violates the primary key constraint 

Try changing your sql statement to be 

`UPDATE PETS SET PETPHOTO=?, PETTYPE=?, COLOR=?,GENDER=?,ISSTERILIZED=?,PEDIGREE=?,DATE_ENTRY=?,VACCINE1=?,VACCINE2=?,VACCINE3=? WHERE PETNAME=?`

this is presuming the `PETNAME` is the primary key ? Otherwise some more work will have to be done to get the ID of the row you want to update

**Update**

With your recent update to your sql you have to adjust your prepared statement parameters. `PETNAME` was moved to the last position so that should be spot 11 and the others should be adjusted accordingly

    pstmt.setString(11, petname);
    pstmt.setString(1, petphoto);
    pstmt.setString(2, pettype);
    pstmt.setString(3, color);
    pstmt.setInt(4, gender);
